{{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Elizabeth Hazelton Haight | honorific_suffix = | image = Elizabeth_Hazelton_Haight.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | occupation = Academic, scholar | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1872|12|11|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[Auburn, New York|Auburn]], New York, United States | death_date = {{Death date|1964|11|15|mf=y}} | death_place = [[Beacon, New York|Beacon]], New York, United States | death_cause = | discipline = [[Classics]] | sub_discipline = [[Latin literature]], [[Ancient Greek literature|Greek poetry]] | alma_mater = [[Cornell University]] | thesis_year = 1909 | workplaces = Vassar College | awards = }}
'''Elizabeth Hazelton Haight''' (February 11, 1872 - November 15, 1964) was an [[United States|American]] [[Classics scholar|classical scholar]] and [[academia|academic]] who specialised in Latin teaching. She spent most of her career working for [[Vassar College]] in [[Poughkeepsie (town), New York|Poughkeepsie]], [[New York (state)|New York]].
==Career== "Hazel" Haight was born in [[Auburn, New York|Auburn]], to John White Haight and Helen M. (Meeker) Haight. Her father was one of the leading businessmen in Auburn during his lifetime.<ref>{{cite web |title=John White Haight (1815-1895) - Find A Grave... |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/65433891/john-white-haight |website=www.findagrave.com |date=27 October 1975}}</ref>
Haight matriculated at [[Vassar College]] in 1890, and was commencement speaker for her undegraduate class, graduating from Vassar in 1894. She also edited the Yearbook for that year.<ref name='ClassWorld' /> She received her [[Master of Arts|AM]], also from Vassar, in 1899, with a dissertation entitled "Conditional Sentences in the Iliad and the Odyssey."<ref name='ClassWorld' /> She then moved to [[Cornell University]], where she studied with [[Charles E. Bennett (scholar)|Charles E. Bennett]], and received her PhD with a thesis titled "The Sea in Greek Poetry" in 1909.<ref name=MemMin>{{cite web |url=https://digitallibrary.vassar.edu/islandora/object/vassar%3A31891#page/1/mode/1up |title=Haight, Elizabeth Hazelton, 1872-1964 - Memorial Minute |publisher=Vassar College |author1=Erck, M. E. |author2=Erck, T. H. |author3=Ryberg, I. S. |accessdate=2017-05-09}}</ref><ref name='ClassWorld'>{{cite journal |author1=Lateiner, D. |date=1996–1997 |title=Elizabeth Hazelton Haight (1872-1964) |journal=The Classical World |volume=90 |issue=2/3 |pages=153–166}}</ref> During her graduate study she held teaching posts in preparatory schools in [[New York State]].<ref name='ClassWorld' /> She returned to Vassar to join its faculty in 1902 and became chair of the Latin department from 1923 until her retirement in 1942.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1964/11/16/elizabeth-hazelton-haight-dies.html?_r=0 |title=Elizabeth Hazelton Haight Dies |publisher=New York Times Archives |accessdate=2017-05-09}}</ref> She was promoted to professor in 1922, 12 years after becoming an associate professor, partly due to the strong written support of [[Grace Macurdy]], another pioneering female classicist at Vassar.<ref name="McManus">{{cite book |last1=McManus |first1=Barbara |title=The Drunken Duchess of Vassar: Grace Harriet Macurdy, Pioneering Feminist Classical Scholar by Barbara McManus |date=2017 |publisher=Ohio State Press |url=https://ohiostatepress.org/books/titles/9780814213278.html}}</ref>{{rp|120}} In her correspondence, Macurdy praised Haight for her "executive ability" and described her as a teacher "whose enthusiasm and genuine love for her subject infect her classes."<ref name="McManus"/>{{rp|120}} Haight's association with Macurdy continued throughout her career, as both taught together at Vassar for the remainder of their careers, and became close friends.<ref name="McManus" />{{rp|i}} This association also included their shared efforts in the public campaign to resist the removal of [[Bert Hodge Hill]] from his position at the [[American School of Classical Studies at Athens]] in the 1920s.<ref name="McManus" />{{rp|152–65}}
Haight died in [[Beacon, New York|Beacon]], [[Dutchess County, New York|Dutchess County]] and is buried in [[Fort Hill Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Elizabeth Hazelton Haight - Find A Grave|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/65433885/elizabeth-hazelton-haight}}</ref>
Haight was the first woman to chair the Advisory Council of the then [[American School of Classical Studies at Rome]]. She was also elected as president of the [[American Philological Association]] in 1934 - the second woman to hold that post.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dbcs.rutgers.edu/index.php?page=person&id=590 |title=HAIGHT, Elizabeth Hazelton |publisher=Database of Classical Scholars |accessdate=2017-05-09}}</ref> She gave her presidential address on "Prose Fiction in the Augustan Age."<ref name='ClassWorld' /> During the mid-1930s, many scholars were emigrating from Germany under Nazi rule; Haight organised a programme of these visiting scholars to Vassar College.<ref name=MemMin />
During her long residency at Vassar College, Haight opened and voluntarily curated the Vassar Classical Museum and bought objects and inscriptions for it. This appreciation for the contributions of archaeology to a classical education was described by Donald Lateiner as "ahead of its time".<ref name='ClassWorld' /> She also wrote a history of the college, along with [[James Monroe Taylor]], its president from 1886 to 1914.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Haight |first1=Elizabeth Hazelton |last2=Taylor |first2=James Monroe |title=Vassar |date=1915 |publisher=Palala Press |isbn=9781347241851 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Vassar-Elizabeth-Hazelton-Haight/dp/134724185X |language=English}}</ref>
==Selected publications== * ''The Autobiography and Letters of Matthew Vassar''. New York, 1916. * ''Life and Letters of James M. Taylor''. New York, 1919. {{OCLC|3433918}} * ''Italy Old and New''. New York, 1922. * ''Horace and His Art of Enjoyment''. New York, 1925. {{OCLC|250063956}} * ''Apuleius and His Influence''. New York, 1927. Nachdruck, 1963. {{OCLC|367528670}} * ''Romance in the Latin Elegiac Poets''. New York, 1932. {{OCLC|938038}} * ''Essays on Ancient Fiction''. New York, 1936. Nachdruck Freeport (New York), 1966. {{OCLC|39970129}} * ''The Roman Use of Anecdotes in Cicero, Livy and the Satirists''. New York, 1940. * ''Essays on the Greek Romances''. New York 1943. {{OCLC|251464618}}; Nachdruck Port Washington (New York), 1965. * ''More Essays on the Greek Romances''. New York, 1945. {{OCLC|459716756}} * ''The Symbolism of the House Door in Classical Poetry''. New York, 1950. {{OCLC|906181909}} * ''Aspects of Symbolism in the Latin Anthology and in Classical and Renaissance Art''. New York, 1952. * ''Pseudo-Callisthenes, Life of Alexander''. New York, 1955. {{OCLC|459039241}}
