The '''[[Ceremonial mace|Mace]] of the Philippine Senate''' is used as the symbol of authority in the [[Senate of the Philippines]].
[[File:JV Ejercito at Philippine Senate rostrum.jpg|thumb|Senator [[JV Ejercito]] presides a session of the Senate of the Philippines. At his right is the mace of the Senate.]] It represents the authority of the President of the Senate and also the authority of the [[Sergeant-at-Arms]] when enforcing order in the institution. It is considered a significant part of the Senate's [[regalia]] and is a symbol of the institution being properly constituted.When the Senate is in session, where it is displayed at the Senate President's rostrum. If the Senate is not in session, it is kept under the custody of the Sergeant-at-Arms.<ref name=symbol>{{cite web|title=Symbols of Authority |url=http://www.senate.gov.ph/about/symbols%20of%20authority.asp#Eagle_(The_Sinister_Side) |publisher=Senate of the Philippines |accessdate=4 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627165803/https://www.senate.gov.ph/about/symbols%20of%20authority.asp |archivedate=27 June 2015 |df= }}</ref>
The Sergeant-at-Arms, is designated as custodian of the mace. At certain occasions such as disorder in the session hall, the official shall lift the mace from its pedestal and present it before an unruly member in order to restore order or quell boisterous behavior in the Chamber.<ref name=symbol/>
