'''The North Wind and the Sun''' is one of [[Aesop's Fables]] ([[Perry Index]] 46). It is type 298 (Wind and Sun) in the [[Aarne-Thompson classification system#Other Animals and Objects 220–299|Aarne-Thompson]] folktale classification.<ref>D. L. Ashliman, ''[http://www.pitt.edu/~dash/type0298.html Wind and Sun: fables of Aarne-Thompson-Uther type 298 in which the wind and the sun dispute about which of them is more powerful plus a related African-American tale]''</ref> The moral it teaches about the superiority of [[persuasion]] over force has made the story widely known. It has also become a chosen text for phonetic transcriptions.

==Story and application==
[[File:The North Wind and the Sun - Wind - Project Gutenberg etext 19994.jpg|thumb|The wind attempts to strip the traveler of his cloak, illustrated by [[Milo Winter]] in a 1919 [[Aesop]] [[anthology]].]]
[[File:The North Wind and the Sun - Sun - Project Gutenberg etext 19994.jpg|thumb|The sun persuades the traveler to take off his cloak]]
The story concerns a competition between the [[North Wind]] and the [[Sun]] to decide which is the stronger of the two. The challenge was to make a passing traveler remove his cloak. However hard the North Wind blew, the traveler only wrapped his cloak tighter to keep warm, but when the Sun shone, the traveler was overcome with heat and soon took his cloak off.

The fable was well known in [[Ancient Greece]]; [[Athenaeus]] records that [[Hieronymus of Rhodes]], in his ''Historical Notes'', quoted an epigram of [[Sophocles]] against [[Euripides]] that parodied the story of [[Helios]] and [[Boreas (god)|Boreas]].<ref>{{cite book | title=Lyco and Traos and Hieronymus of Rhodes: Text, Translation, and Discussion | editor1-last=Fortenbaugh | editor1-first=William Wall | editor2-last=White | editor2-first=Stephen Augustus | series=Rutgers University Studies in Classical Humanities | volume=XII | publisher=Transaction Publishers | date=2004 | page=161 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zdesXRC6ba8C&pg=PA161 | accessdate=2014-02-09 }}</ref> It related how Sophocles had his cloak stolen by a boy to whom he had made love. Euripides joked that he had had that boy too, and it did not cost him anything. Sophocles' reply satirises the adulteries of Euripides:
"It was the Sun, and not a boy, whose heat stripped me naked;
as for you, Euripides, when you were kissing someone else's wife
the North Wind screwed ''you''. You are unwise, you who sow
in another's field, to accuse Eros of being a snatch-thief."

The Latin version of the fable first appeared centuries later in [[Avianus]], as ''De Vento et Sole'' (Of the wind and the sun, Fable 4);<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mythfolklore.net/aesopica/avianus/4.htm |title=Mythfolklore.net |publisher=Mythfolklore.net |date= |accessdate=2013-03-23}}</ref> early versions in English and [[Johann Gottfried Herder]]'s poetic version in German (''Wind und Sonne'') also gave it as such. It was only in mid-Victorian times that the title "The North Wind and the Sun" began to be used. In fact, the Avianus poem refers to the characters as [[Anemoi#Boreas|Boreas]] and [[Apollo#Greco-Roman epithets|Phoebus]], the divinities of the north wind and the sun, and it was under the title ''Phébus et Borée'' that it appeared in [[La Fontaine's Fables]].

[[Gilles Corrozet]], who had compiled a fable collection in French verse earlier than La Fontaine, twice featured the contest between the sun and the wind in his [[emblem book]]s. In ''Hecatomgraphie'' (1540), the first of these, the story is told in a quatrain, accompanied by a woodcut in which a man holds close a fur cloak under the wintry blast while on the other side he strips naked beneath the sun’s rays. It is titled with the moral “More by gentleness than strength” (''Plus par doulceur que par force'').<ref>[http://www.emblems.arts.gla.ac.uk/french/facsimile.php?id=sm385-e2v Glasgow University]</ref> The same illustration was used to accompany another poem in Corrozet’s later ''Emblemes'' (1543), which counsels taking enjoyment and being careful as necessity demands, wisely adapting oneself to circumstances in the same way as one dresses differently for winter than for summer.<ref>[http://www.emblems.arts.gla.ac.uk/french/facsimile.php?id=sm384-63r Emblem 63]</ref>

Victorian versions of the fable give the moral as "Persuasion is better than force", but it had been put in different ways at other times. In the Barlow edition of 1667, [[Aphra Behn]] taught the [[Stoicism|Stoic]] lesson that there should be moderation in everything: "In every passion moderation choose,/For all extremes do bad effects produce",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mythfolklore.net/aesopica/barlow/34.htm |title=Mythfolklore.net |publisher=Mythfolklore.net |date= |accessdate=2013-03-23}}</ref>. In the 18th century, Herder came to the theological conclusion that, while superior force leaves us cold, the warmth of Christ's love dispels it,<ref>''Gedichte V, Geschichte und Fabel 4'', quoted in the [[:de:Die Sonne und der Wind|German Wikipedia]]</ref> and Walter Crane's limerick version of 1887 gives a psychological interpretation, "True strength is not bluster". But for [[Guy Wetmore Carryl]] in his humorous rewriting of the fable, "The Impetuous Breeze and the Diplomatic Sun", tact is the lesson to be learned. There the competition is between the man and the wind; the sun only demonstrates the right way of achieving one's end.<ref>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Impetuous_Breeze_and_the_Diplomatic_Sun Fables for the Frivolous (1898)]</ref>

While most examples draw a moral lesson, La Fontaine's "Mildness more than violence achieves" (''Fables'' VI.3) hints at the political application that was present also in Avianus' conclusion: "They cannot win who start with threats". There is evidence that this reading has had an explicit influence on the diplomacy of modern times: in South Korea's [[Sunshine Policy]], for instance, or Japanese relations with the [[State Peace and Development Council|military regime in Myanmar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burmalibrary.org/docs/NorthWind&Sun.htm |title=Burmalibrary.org |publisher=Burmalibrary.org |date= |accessdate=2013-03-23}}</ref>

==The fable in the arts==
[[Jean II Restout|Jean Restout]] made a painting of La Fontaine's fable for the [[Hôtel de Soubise]] in 1738. This showed a traveller on horseback among mountains under a stormy sky.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://worldvisitguide.com/oeuvre/photo_ME0000063188.html |title=Worldvisitguide.com |publisher=Worldvisitguide.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-23}}</ref> In his print of the same subject, [[Jean-Baptiste Oudry]] reversed the perspective to show the god riding a cloud chariot with the horseback traveller merely a small figure below.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/Wave/image/joconde/0379/m078402_0000717_p.jpg |title=Culture.gouv.fr |date= |accessdate=2013-03-23}}</ref> This too was the perspective of [[Gustave Moreau]]'s 1879 watercolour in the series he painted of the fables.<ref>[https://theartstack.com/artist/gustave-moreau/phebus-et-boree-1879 Art Stack]</ref> In modern times, the fable has been made into a 3-minute animated film for children by the [[National Film Board of Canada]] (1972).<ref>''The North Wind and the Sun: A Fable by Aesop''. [http://nfb.ca/film/north_wind_and_sun_fable_by_aesop View online]</ref> It also figured as part of a 1987 set of Greek stamps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creighton.edu/aesop/artifacts/stamps/greece/index.php |title=The 5 drachma value |publisher=Creighton.edu |date=1987-03-05 |accessdate=2013-03-23}}</ref>

[[File:Phébus&Borée.jpg|thumb|left|250px|[[Jean-Baptiste Oudry]]'s cosmic interpretation of La Fontaine's fable, 1729/34]]
The fable was the third of five in [[Anthony Plog]]'s "Aesop’s Fables" for narrator, piano and horn (1989/93);<ref>A performance on [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fxqCfvmPYVo You Tube]</ref> it is also one of the five pieces in [[Bob Chilcott]]'s "Aesop's Fables" for piano and choir (2008).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EN_fOMt-IVE |title=There is a performance on YouTube |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-23}}</ref> And, under the title "The Wind and the Sun", the English composer Philip Godfrey (b.1964) has made a setting for children's choir and piano.<ref>[http://www.philipgodfrey.co.uk/upper-voices.htm Compser’s website with sample score]</ref>

La Fontaine's ''Phébus et Borée'' was choreographed in 2006 by [[:fr:Karine Ponties|Karine Ponties]] as part of Annie Sellem's composite ballet production of La Fontaine's fables as a 25-minute performance for a male and female dancer.<ref>The last four minutes can be seen on [http://vimeo.com/5838460 Vimeo]</ref> Its creator has commented on the fable's theme that 'it demonstrates people's vulnerability to cosmic forces and the inner links there are between natural events and our life as humans.'<ref>''Il y montre aussi la vulnérabilité de l’homme face aux jeux cosmiques et les liens profonds qu’il y a entre les grandes forces physiques de notre monde et la vie humaine'', [http://www.damedepic.be/Public/Projet.php?ID=3451 Dame de Pic]</ref> But for the Scottish artist Jane Topping (b. 1972), who referenced "The North Wind and the Sun" in her 2009 installation, the fable is to be interpreted in the context of subliminal persuasion via images.<ref>A photo on the [http://www.janetopping.co.uk/exhibitions/persuasion/index.php artist's website]{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>

In 2011 Anat Pollack used solo ballet as part of her video installation "The North Wind and the Sun", addressing much the same themes as Karine Ponties and Jane Topping. Her artistic statement points out that 'Advanced communication and information systems are altering how information is interpreted and perceived. Interactions within our environments are increasingly information based, ephemeral, and less concrete. To understand how these changes are impacting our personal and social spaces, I have focused on a study of information processing, and the way that memory functions to locate the individual within their world.' <ref>[http://www.anatpollack.net/artist%20statement.php The artist's website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130821031824/http://www.anatpollack.net/artist%20statement.php |date=2013-08-21 }} also has a copy of the video</ref> All are concerned with the subtle means by which individuals can be manipulated. From this wary point of view, the sun's way of communication may differ in kind but has the same end in view.

==Use in phonetic demonstrations==
[[File:Recording of speaker of British English (Received Pronunciation).ogg|thumb|right|''The North Wind and the Sun'' read with [[Received Pronunciation]]]] The fable is made famous by its use in [[phonetic]] descriptions of [[language]]s as an illustration of spoken language. In the ''Handbook of the [[International Phonetic Association]]'' and the ''[[Journal of the International Phonetic Association]]'', a translation of the fable into each language described is transcribed into the [[International Phonetic Alphabet]]. It is recommended by the IPA for the purpose of eliciting all phonemic contrasts that occur in English when conducting tests by foreign users or of regional usage.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:NB0H9qpVsA4J:citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download%3Fdoi%3D10.1.1.149.5276%26rep%3Drep1%26type%3Dpdf+north+wind+and+the+sun+comparative+linguistics&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESgo6QPL2r_ZZI9HW-rXekr2Gtm8TDtAgG6uQnpuMOLg9FsqrwrZjYBplXyh_EaGwKrvHCIUH3gC3vtVLlQyb52yGJFxtLI_uQtAMHu4A2lnhYBDS_o958tbtFqRGqhyZE74mUrv&sig=AHIEtbQoxfTT0nfEThll3PRUC7uXjD4NGQ |title=See for example this investigation |publisher=Docs.google.com |date= |accessdate=2013-03-23}}</ref> For example, the description of [[American English]] in the ''Handbook of the International Phonetic Association'' includes the following as a sample text:<ref>International Phonetic Association (1999), p. 44.</ref>

;Broad transcription
:{{IPA|ðə ˈnoɹθ ˌwɪnd ən (ð)ə ˈsʌn wɚ dɪsˈpjutɪŋ ˈwɪtʃ wəz ðə ˈstɹɑŋɡɚ, wɛn ə ˈtɹævəlɚ ˌkem əˈlɑŋ ˈɹæpt ɪn ə ˈwoɹm ˈklok.}}
:{{IPA|ðe əˈɡɹid ðət ðə ˈwʌn hu ˈfɚst səkˈsidəd ɪn ˈmekɪŋ ðə ˈtɹævəlɚ ˈtek ɪz ˈklok ˌɑf ʃʊd bi kənˈsɪdɚd ˈstɹɑŋɡɚ ðən ðɪ ˈəðɚ.}}
:{{IPA|ðɛn ðə ˈnoɹθ ˌwɪnd ˈblu əz ˈhɑɹd əz i ˈkʊd, bət ðə ˈmoɹ hi ˈblu ðə ˈmoɹ ˈklosli dɪd ðə ˈtɹævlɚ ˈfold hɪz ˈklok əˈɹaʊnd ɪm;}}
:{{IPA|ˌæn ət ˈlæst ðə ˈnoɹθ ˌwɪnd ˌɡev ˈʌp ði əˈtɛmpt. ˈðɛn ðə ˈsʌn ˈʃaɪnd ˌaʊt ˈwoɹmli ənd ɪˈmidiətli ðə ˈtɹævlɚ ˈtʊk ˌɑf ɪz ˈklok.}}
:{{IPA|ən ˈso ðə ˈnoɹθ ˌwɪnd wəz əˈblaɪʒ tɪ kənˈfɛs ðət ðə ˈsʌn wəz ðə ˈstɹɑŋɡɚ əv ðə ˈtu.}}

;Narrow transcription (differences emphasized)
:{{IPA|ðə ˈnɔɹθ ˌwɪnd ən '''ə''' ˈsʌn wɚ '''dɪsˈpjuɾɪŋ''' ˈwɪtʃ wəz ðə ˈstɹɑŋɡɚ, wɛn ə ˈ'''tɹævlɚ''' ˌkem əˈlɑŋ ˈɹæpt ɪn ə ˈwɔɹm ˈklok.}}
:{{IPA|ðe əˈɡɹid ðət ðə ˈwʌn hu ˈfɚst səkˈsidəd ɪn ˈmekɪŋ ðə ˈ'''tɹævlɚ''' ˈtek ɪz ˈklok ˌɑf ʃʊd bi kənˈsɪdɚd ˈstɹɑŋɡɚ ðən ðɪ ˈ'''ʌðɚ'''.}}
:{{IPA|ðɛn ðə ˈnɔɹθ ˌwɪnd ˈblu əz ˈhɑɹd əz '''hi''' ˈkʊd, bət ðə ˈmɔɹ hi ˈblu ðə ˈmɔɹ ˈklosli dɪd ðə ˈtɹævlɚ ˈfold hɪz ˈklok əˈɹaʊnd '''hɪm''';}}
:{{IPA|ˌæn ət ˈlæst ðə ˈnɔɹθ ˌwɪnd ˌɡev ˈʌp ði əˈtɛmpt. ˈðɛn ðə ˈsʌn ˈʃaɪnd ˌaʊt ˈwɔɹmli ənd ɪˈmidiətli ðə ˈtɹævlɚ ˈtʊk ˌɑf ɪz klok.}}
:{{IPA|ən ˈso ðə ˈnɔɹθ ˌwɪnd wəz əˈblaɪʒ tɪ kənˈfɛs ðət ðə ˈsʌn wəz ðə ˈstɹɑŋɡɚ əv ðə ˈtu.}}

;Orthographic version
:''The North Wind and the Sun were disputing which was the stronger, when a traveler came along wrapped in a warm cloak.''
:''They agreed that the one who first succeeded in making the traveler take his cloak off should be considered stronger than the other.''
:''Then the North Wind blew as hard as he could, but the more he blew the more closely did the traveler fold his cloak around him;''
:''and at last the North Wind gave up the attempt. Then the Sun shined out warmly, and immediately the traveler took off his cloak.''
:''And so the North Wind was obliged to confess that the Sun was the stronger of the two.''

The fable has also been proposed as a [[parallel text]] in [[comparative linguistics]] as it provides more natural language than the [[Lord's Prayer#Use as a language comparison tool|Lord's Prayer]]. In addition, impromptu tellings can indicate differences within languages such as [[dialects]] or national varieties.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Post|first=Margje|year=2007|title=“Frog Story” and “Map Task” in the Russian countryside|journal=Poljarnyj Vestnik|issue=10|doi=10.7557/6.1316|url=https://septentrio.uit.no/index.php/vestnik/article/viewFile/1316/1252}}</ref> The example above, for instance, has ''shined'' where [[British English]] usage is ''shone''.<ref>See {{cite journal|last=Roach|first=Peter|title=British English (Received Pronunciation)|journal=Journal of the International Phonetic Association|date=November 2004|volume=34|issue=2|pages=239–245|doi=10.1017/s0025100304001768}} Wikipedia Commons provides a scan of this [[:Image:Phonetic and phonemic transcriptions of audio record of Received Pronunciation.jpg|here]] and the corresponding audio file [[:File:Recording of speaker of British English (Received Pronunciation).ogg|here]].</ref> The previous IPA handbook transcribed ''shone'' for the Southern British and Scottish versions, but ''began to shine'' for the American English version.<ref>''The Principles of the International Phonetic Association'' (1949), being a description of the International Phonetic Alphabet and the manner of using it, illustrated by texts in 51 languages.</ref> For an illustration of [[New Zealand English]], the fable was replaced by "The Southerly Wind and the Sun" to make it geographically appropriate.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bauer|first1=Laurie|last2=Bardsley|first2=Dianne|last3=Kennedy|first3=Marianna|last4=Major|first4=George|year=2007|title=New Zealand English|journal=Journal of the International Phonetic Association|volume=37|issue=1|pages=97–102|doi=10.1017/S0025100306002830|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/services/aop-cambridge-core/content/view/715F8488473630A0123E5F3527023346/S0025100306002830a.pdf/new_zealand_english.pdf}}</ref>

